// 00-hello.mn — Curriculum entry: the kernel surfaces in one program
//
// Mentl's eight kernel primitives (DESIGN.md §0.5) are not eight
// features. They are eight ways the same medium reads itself. This
// program is the smallest one that demonstrates all eight at once.
// Every line clears the eight interrogations (CLAUDE.md ⌁ Mentl's
// anchor): Graph? Handler? Verb? Row? Ownership? Refinement? Gradient?
// Reason?
//
// To run:    mentl compile tutorial/00-hello | wat2wasm - -o /tmp/h.wasm && wasmtime /tmp/h.wasm
// To edit:   mentl edit tutorial/00-hello       — the medium opens; type ?? to see the gradient narrow
// To audit:  mentl audit tutorial/00-hello      — eight tentacles project the file's capability set

import runtime/io

/// greet — the curriculum's first read.
///
/// The eight, in residue form:
///   #1 Graph + Env   — `name` is a handle; the graph chases it through unification.
///   #2 Handlers      — `print_string` is performed against the chain (wasi_filesystem absorbs IO).
///   #3 Verbs         — `|>` flows; `~>` attaches; same source, two reads.
///   #4 Row algebra   — `with !Alloc` proves zero allocation under inference (real-time eligible).
///   #5 Ownership     — `ref` borrows the string; greet returns Unit; no ownership transfer.
///   #6 Refinement    — invariants enforced by construction; verify.mn discharges decidable
///                       predicates at compile time (see 06-refinement.mn).
///   #7 Gradient      — `with !Alloc` is a gradient annotation Mentl can propose; type `??`
///                       on the row to ask "what would this unlock?"
///   #8 Reasons       — every unification leaves a Located/Inferred edge in the graph; the
///                       Why Engine walks them on demand via `mentl query reason name`.
fn greet(ref name) with !Alloc = {
  "Hello, "
    |> str_concat(name)
    |> str_concat(". The medium is reading you back.\n")
    |> print_string
}

fn main() = {
  greet("kernel")
  greet("oracle")
  greet("octopus")
}
